# Forward PWAs still re-fetching the old hashed manifest URL (now gone)
# to the stable path. `_redirects` fire even when no asset matches.
# Removable in ~a month, once most installs have refreshed.
#
# Anchor the match to the `.webmanifest` extension: a bare `manifest-*`
# splat also swallows hashed route chunks like `manifest-route-<hash>.js`
# (301'd to JSON, they break the gallery's dynamic import). The `:hash`
# placeholder matches any non-`/` run — hyphenated hashes included — while
# the trailing literal keeps it scoped to the old manifest asset.
/_build/assets/manifest-:hash.webmanifest  /manifest.webmanifest  301

# Serve the flattened `/beam/with/:endpoint` shell for every endpoint id. The
# id is a live client-side relay handle, so no per-id page can be prerendered
# (Cloudflare's static assets match literal paths only — no `[param]` filename
# routing); without this a cold load falls through to the 404 shell and the
# client hydrates a beam route against 404 markup, throwing a hydration error.
# A 200 rewrite (not a redirect) keeps the id in the URL for the client router.
# `:endpoint` matches a single segment. The target is the extensionless
# `/beam/__endpoint` (served from `/beam/__endpoint.html`): Cloudflare strips a
# trailing `/index` or `.html` from the target and 307s to the stripped path, so
# naming the `.html` here would bounce every id to a bare `/beam/__endpoint`,
# dropping it from the URL. The target sits one level up from `/beam/with/`, a
# prefix the source can't match, so the stripped form never renormalizes into
# `/beam/with/:endpoint` and trips loop detection.
/beam/with/:endpoint  /beam/__endpoint  200
